It is important to define `thisClass` as **private** because:&lt;br/&gt;
1) it must not be inherited: derived classes must either define their own `thisClass` or produce an error message&lt;br/&gt;
2) references from other classes should be done as `ClassName.class` rather than `ClassName.thisClass`.

With `thisClass` defined, access to the class name becomes:

    thisClass.getName()

So, we have a situation when we need to statically get class object or a class full/simple name without an explicit usage of `MyClass.class` syntax.

It can be really handy in some cases, e.g. logger instance for the [tag:kotlin] upper-level functions (in this case kotlin creates a static Java class not accessible from the kotlin code).

We have a few different variants for getting this info:

 1. &lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    ```new Object(){}.getClass().getEnclosingClass();```&lt;br&gt;
    noted by [Tom Hawtin - tackline](https://stackoverflow.com/a/936724/1816338)

 2. &lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    ```getClassContext()[0].getName();``` from the `SecurityManager`&lt;br&gt;
    noted by [Christoffer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/936776/1816338)

 3. &lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    ```new Throwable().getStackTrace()[0].getClassName();```&lt;br&gt;
    by [count ludwig](https://stackoverflow.com/a/1577359/1816338)

 4. &lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    ```Thread.currentThread().getStackTrace()[1].getClassName();```&lt;br&gt;
    from [Keksi](https://stackoverflow.com/a/2971457/1816338)

 5. and finally awesome&lt;br&gt;
